---
title: Minty Lamb and Apricot Meatballs with Tomato Pearl Barley Risotto
description: When most people watch the meatball scene in Lady and the Tramp, they see romance. They coo and giggle. Now, while that’s all very nice, all I saw was a very relatable, very terrifying struggle to get the last meatball! Did anyone else feel that way? Now, take those meatballs and multiply their deliciousness by 100 or so and you have our minty lamb and apricot meatballs. Cook these up and make sure you get one extra for all your hard work!
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/56434db14dab7190038b4567.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipecards/card/56434db14dab7190038b4567.pdf
time required: 40 minutes
cuisine: Mediterranean
nutrition:
  calories: 786 kcal
  fat: 26 g
  saturated fat: 12 g
  carbohydrates: 104 g
  protein: 35 g
course: main course
author: HelloFresh
servings: 2
source: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipes/minty-lamb-and-apricot-meatballs-56434db14dab7190038b4567
---

Peel and chop your @onion{1}(peeled and chopped into 2cm pieces). Peel and chop your @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and chopped) and chop your @dried apricots{4} into very small pieces, about ½cm (if your knife skills allow!). Chop the green leafy part and the root from the @leek{1} and discard these, slice the leek in half and then very thinly slice widthways. Roughly chop the @mint{3}(roughly chopped).

Put a #saucepan{} on a medium heat with @oil{3%tbsp} and add the onion, garlic and leek. Cook for about ~{5%minutes} with a @salt{pinch} and a @ground black pepper{grind} until everything has softened. Spoon roughly a third of this mixture into a #bowl{} and set aside for later (you'll use it for the meatballs!).

Add the @pearl barley{3/4%cup} to the saucepan with the onion mixture and stir, so that the pearl barley has a nice coating of oil.

Tip in your @chopped tomatoes{1%400g can} along with @water{400%ml} and @chicken stock pot{1/2}. Add @salt{1/4%tsp}, a @ground black pepper{grind} and @sugar{1/2%tsp} (if you have any). Bring to the boil and then turn down the heat and simmer the risotto gently for about ~{30%minutes} or until the pearl barley is tender and the liquid has been absorbed.

> Stir occasionally to stop the risotto sticking to the bottom of the pan!

> If the risotto dries out before the pearl barley is cooked, simply add a splash more water.

While your risotto is cooking, tackle the meatballs! Add your @lamb mince{250%g}, apricots, @panko breadcrumbs{3%tbsp} and three quarters of your chopped mint to the onion, garlic and leek mixture you set aside earlier in step 2. Season with @salt{1/4%tsp} and a @ground black pepper{grind} and mix well.

> Using your hands to mix combines everything much more effectively, so don't be afraid to get stuck in there!

Shape the mixture into roughly 12 equal-sized small meatballs (about the diameter of a 50p piece). Heat @oil{1%tbsp} in a #frying pan{} and cook your meatballs for about ~{8-9%minutes} in total, or until each side is nicely browned and the meatballs are cooked through. Remember to turn them every couple of mins.

> Turn them gently so they don't break up.

Set them aside in the pan until the risotto is finished.

When the pearl barley is tender and has absorbed all the liquid, check for seasoning and add more @salt{} and @ground black pepper{grind} to taste. Serve topped with your meatballs and sprinkle the rest of your mint over. Yum!